    <h1>Best SIP Amount by Salary in India 2026 — How Much Should You Invest?</h1>
    <div class="article-dateline">
      <span>Published: March 26, 2026</span> · <span>{% set author = authors[authorId] %}By <a href="{{ author.url }}">{{ author.name }}</a><svg class="verified-badge" aria-label="Verified author" title="Verified" viewBox="0 0 20 20" width="14" height="14" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><circle cx="10" cy="10" r="10" fill="#1d9bf0"/><path d="M6 10.5l2.5 2.5L14 7.5" stroke="white" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>, {{ author.credentials }}</span>
    </div>

    <p class="blog-article__intro">"How much SIP should I start?" is the most common question from first-time investors in India. The honest answer: it depends on your salary, your goals, and your existing obligations. But here is a salary-wise breakdown with real numbers — so you stop guessing and start investing with a plan.</p>

    <div class="definition-block">
      <p><strong>The 20% rule:</strong> A widely used starting point for SIP investment is 20% of your monthly in-hand salary. This is not a ceiling — it is a floor. As income grows and liabilities reduce, the target should rise to 30–40%.</p>
    </div>

