    <h2>Mistakes First-Time SIP Investors Make</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Starting too small and never increasing:</strong> ₹500/month is fine to start, but if it stays at ₹500 for 5 years, you have lost five years of meaningful compounding. Step up every April.</li>
      <li><strong>Stopping SIP during a market fall:</strong> The worst time to stop SIP is exactly when markets are cheap. Every unit you buy in a bear market costs less — stopping is buying at full price only.</li>
      <li><strong>Too many funds:</strong> Three or more SIPs running in funds with high portfolio overlap does not diversify — it just creates admin work. Two or three well-chosen funds is optimal.</li>
      <li><strong>Ignoring goal alignment:</strong> An SIP for retirement needs 20+ years and equity-heavy funds. An SIP for a house down payment in 5 years needs hybrid or debt-oriented funds.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">How much SIP should I do with ₹30,000 salary?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">With ₹30,000 monthly in-hand, aim for ₹5,000–6,000 in SIP (20% rule). After building a ₹90,000–1,00,000 emergency fund, increase the SIP to ₹8,000–9,000. Even ₹3,000/month started at 24 and stepped up 10% annually builds ₹1.2 crore by 50.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">How much SIP is needed for ₹1 crore in 10 years?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">To accumulate ₹1 crore in 10 years at 12% CAGR, you need approximately ₹43,000/month. At 14%, it drops to ₹36,000/month. For most salaries, a 10-year ₹1 crore target requires high income or high savings rate — use our <a href="/india/sip-calculator/">SIP calculator</a> to find the exact amount for your timeline.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What is the ideal SIP amount for ₹1 lakh salary?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">For a ₹1 lakh monthly in-hand salary, a minimum SIP of ₹20,000/month (20%) is appropriate. Recommended target is ₹30,000/month (30%). With a 10% annual step-up, starting at ₹20,000 at age 30 builds approximately ₹5.2 crore by age 55.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Can I start SIP with ₹500 per month?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Yes — many fund houses allow SIPs from ₹100–500/month. Starting small is better than not starting. But treat ₹500 as a launch pad, not a destination. Commit to increasing your SIP by ₹500–1,000 every 6 months as income allows.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Which SIP gives the highest return in India?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">No fund guarantees the highest return. Historically, small-cap and mid-cap equity funds have delivered 14–18% CAGR over long periods (10+ years), but with high volatility. For most investors, a diversified mix of large-cap index fund (Nifty 50 / Sensex) and a flexi-cap fund delivers stable 11–13% CAGR with lower risk.</div>
    </div>

